ce:section.ce:para:
Coal is a low cost and abundant natural resource. As one of the most important energy sources, coal has been the backbone to humanity and society development, and this will be continued in the coming 20–30 years in some countries such as China [1]. It is well known that coal is largely a combination of amorphous, degraded plant remains that have metamorphosed to varying degrees over time and increased pressure and heat (Fig. 1
                     ). In essence, coal is one of the special natural materials with three-dimensional (3D) crosslinking network, which is composed of aromatic rings and hydroaromatic groups connected by short aliphatic and ether bonds [2]. The organic ingredients in coal are derived from plant remains which have undergone decomposition and complex physical and chemical changes after burial in the earth. The carbon content in coal increases with the increase of the coalification degree, resulting in the increased sp
                     2 hybridized carbons. Thus far, coal has been widely and mainly used as an energy source, nevertheless, the inherent advantages of coal make it attractive as resources to prepare functional carbon materials, evidenced by many publications in the past decades.

The combination of CCMs and metal or metal compound can enhance the capacitance performance. Nanoporous carbon/MnO2 composites with a SSA of 1700 m2 g−
                        1 were fabricated from CTP and manganese dioxide by Tomko et al. [143], showing an improved electrochemical performance for supercapacitors. Qiu group [98] used coal-derived graphite and Mn3O4 to synthesize GO/Mn3O4 by hydrazine reduction. They also fabricated graphene-noble metal composites (Pt/GS, Ru/GS and PtRu/GS) using coal as carbon precursor [144]. The as-prepared composites showed a SSA of 135 to 306 m2 g−1 and pore size of 3.69 to 4.02 nm, and a good catalytic activity for the selective reduction of nitrogen oxides (Fig. 9
                        ).
